   "body": "# The 6 Scenarios (and the 4 Exercises)\n\nThe exam draws **4 scenarios at random from these 6**. Each frames a set of questions in a realistic production context. The **primary domains** below are the guide's own mapping — worth trusting over any reconstruction, because they tell you which knowledge each scenario will actually probe.\n\n| # | Scenario | The situation | Primary domains |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | **Customer Support Resolution Agent** | An Agent SDK support agent handling returns, billing disputes, and account issues, reaching backend systems through MCP tools (`get_customer`, `lookup_order`, `process_refund`, `escalate_to_human`). Target: 80%+ first-contact resolution **while knowing when to escalate** | D1, D2, D5 |\n| 2 | **Code Generation with Claude Code** | Claude Code for generation, refactoring, debugging, and documentation — integrated into a development workflow with custom slash commands and CLAUDE.md, and a standing question of **plan mode vs direct execution** | D3, D5 |\n| 3 | **Multi-Agent Research System** | A coordinator delegating to specialized subagents — web search, document analysis, synthesis, report generation — producing comprehensive, cited reports | D1, D2, D5 |\n| 4 | **Developer Productivity with Claude** | Tools that help engineers explore unfamiliar codebases, understand legacy systems, generate boilerplate, and automate repetitive tasks, using **built-in tools** (Read, Write, Bash, Grep, Glob) alongside MCP servers | D2, D3, D1 |\n| 5 | **Claude Code for Continuous Integration** | Claude Code inside CI/CD: automated reviews, test generation, PR feedback — with prompts designed for **actionable feedback and minimal false positives** | D3, D4 |\n| 6 | **Structured Data Extraction** | Extraction from unstructured documents, validated against JSON schemas, holding high accuracy, **handling edge cases gracefully**, and feeding downstream systems | D4, D5 |\n\nNotice what the mapping tells you:\n\n- **D5 appears in four of six scenarios.** It carries the lowest weight (15%) but the widest reach — context loss, escalation, error propagation, and provenance are the failure modes that show up everywhere.\n- **D1 and D2 travel together** in the agent-building scenarios (1, 3, 4): you design the tools and the orchestration that consumes them.\n- **Scenario 5 is the only place D4 meets CI** — prompt precision in the service of a review bot, not extraction.\n\n## The 4 preparation exercises\n\nThe guide's §8 prescribes four hands-on exercises. These are, in effect, the **official specification for a practice lab** — build these and you have touched most of the blueprint.\n\n| # | Exercise | What you build | Domains reinforced |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | **Build a Multi-Tool Agent with Escalation Logic** | 3–4 MCP tools with descriptions careful enough to disambiguate two similar ones; an agentic loop switching on `stop_reason`; structured errors with `errorCategory` and `isRetryable`; a hook that blocks a business-rule violation and reroutes to escalation; multi-concern requests decomposed and answered as one | D1, D2, D5 |\n| 2 | **Configure Claude Code for a Team Development Workflow** | Project-level CLAUDE.md; `.claude/rules/` with glob frontmatter; a skill using `context: fork` and `allowed-tools`; an MCP server in `.mcp.json` with env-var expansion plus a personal one in `~/.claude.json`; plan mode vs direct execution tested on tasks of three sizes | D3, D2 |\n| 3 | **Build a Structured Data Extraction Pipeline** | An extraction tool whose schema has required, optional, nullable, and `\"other\"`+detail fields; a validation-retry loop that distinguishes recoverable from unrecoverable failures; few-shot examples for format variety; a 100-document batch handled by `custom_id`; confidence-based routing to human review | D4, D5 |\n| 4 | **Design and Debug a Multi-Agent Research Pipeline** | A coordinator with `\"Task\"` in `allowedTools` delegating to two+ subagents with explicit context passing; parallel Task calls in one response; structured findings carrying claim, evidence, source, and date; a simulated timeout propagated as structured error context; conflicting sources preserved with attribution | D1, D2, D5 |\n\n> Exercises 1 and 4 are close cousins of exam scenarios 1 and 3. If you build only two, build those.",
   "ko": "**요지.** 6개 시나리오 뱅크에서 **4개가 랜덤** 출제. 각 시나리오의 **primary domains는 가이드 §5의 공식 표기**이므로, 이 매핑이 \"그 시나리오에서 실제로 무엇을 물을지\"를 알려준다.\n\n| # | 시나리오 | Primary domains |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Customer Support Resolution Agent | **D1, D2, D5** |\n| 2 | Code Generation with Claude Code | **D3, D5** |\n| 3 | Multi-Agent Research System | **D1, D2, D5** |\n| 4 | Developer Productivity with Claude | **D2, D3, D1** |\n| 5 | Claude Code for Continuous Integration | **D3, D4** |\n| 6 | Structured Data Extraction | **D4, D5** |\n\n**매핑이 말해주는 것 (판단 포인트):**\n- **D5는 6개 중 4개에 등장한다.** 가중치는 15%로 가장 낮은데 **도달 범위는 가장 넓다** — 컨텍스트 유실·에스컬레이션·에러 전파·출처는 어디서나 터지는 실패 모드다. 비중이 낮다고 뒤로 미루면 시나리오 문항에서 반복해서 물린다.\n- **D1과 D2는 함께 다닌다**(시나리오 1·3·4). 도구를 설계하고, 그 도구를 소비하는 오케스트레이션을 설계한다 — 한 몸.\n- **D4가 CI를 만나는 곳은 시나리오 5뿐.** 추출이 아니라 **리뷰 봇의 프롬프트 정밀도**(false positive 억제) 맥락이다.\n\n**§8 준비 연습 4개 = 사실상 공식 실습 사양서.** 시나리오 랩(Pillar ②)은 이걸 그대로 실행하면 된다.\n\n| # | 연습 | 강화 도메인 |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Multi-Tool Agent + 에스컬레이션 로직 (유사 도구 2개 구분 · `stop_reason` 루프 · `errorCategory`/`isRetryable` · 정책 차단 훅) | D1, D2, D5 |\n| 2 | 팀 워크플로우용 Claude Code 구성 (CLAUDE.md · rules glob · `context: fork` 스킬 · `.mcp.json` env 확장 · plan vs direct) | D3, D2 |\n| 3 | 구조화 추출 파이프라인 (nullable/`\"other\"` 스키마 · validation-retry · few-shot · 100건 배치 `custom_id` · confidence 라우팅) | D4, D5 |\n| 4 | 멀티에이전트 리서치 파이프라인 (`allowedTools`에 `\"Task\"` · 명시적 컨텍스트 전달 · 병렬 Task · claim/evidence/source/date · 타임아웃 구조화 전파 · 상충 출처 병기) | D1, D2, D5 |\n\n> **둘만 한다면 1번과 4번.** 각각 시험 시나리오 1·3과 사실상 같은 문제다."
