   "body": "# Scope Boundaries — What Is and Is Not Tested\n\nThe guide's appendix does something unusually generous: it lists what is **explicitly out of scope**. This is the single most efficient page in the guide, because it hands back study time.\n\n## Explicitly out of scope\n\nNone of the following appears on the exam:\n\n- Fine-tuning or training custom models; Claude's internal architecture, training process, or weights\n- Constitutional AI, RLHF, or safety training methodology\n- Claude API authentication, billing, or account management; OAuth, API key rotation, authentication protocols\n- **Deploying or hosting MCP servers** — infrastructure, networking, container orchestration\n- **Streaming API implementation or server-sent events**\n- **Prompt caching implementation details** (beyond knowing that it exists)\n- **Token counting algorithms or tokenization specifics**\n- Rate limiting, quotas, or API pricing calculations\n- Embedding models or vector database implementation\n- Computer use (browser and desktop automation); vision and image analysis\n- Specific cloud provider configuration (AWS, GCP, Azure)\n- Performance benchmarking or model comparison metrics\n- Implementation detail of particular languages and frameworks, beyond what tool and schema configuration requires\n\n**Three of these deserve emphasis, because they are the ones people study anyway:**\n\n1. **MCP transport and server deployment.** MCP is 18% of the exam, and the instinct is to go deep on stdio vs HTTP, trust boundaries, and hardening. The guide's D2 objectives are about **tool descriptions, structured errors, tool distribution, `.mcp.json` scoping, and built-in tools** — not transport, not hosting.\n2. **Prompt caching and token budgeting.** These sound like the heart of \"Context Management,\" but the domain is really about **preserving information** — case facts, escalation triggers, error context, provenance — not about counting tokens.\n3. **Streaming.** Absent entirely.\n\n## Explicitly in scope\n\nThe guide's in-scope list maps cleanly onto the 30 task statements:\n\n**Agents** — agentic loop control flow via `stop_reason`, tool result handling, termination conditions · coordinator-subagent orchestration, task decomposition, parallel spawning, iterative refinement · subagent context passing, structured state persistence, crash recovery via manifests\n\n**Tools and MCP** — tool description quality, splitting vs consolidating, naming to reduce ambiguity · MCP resources for content catalogs vs tools for actions · project vs user scope, env-var expansion, simultaneous multi-server access · structured error responses, transient vs business vs permission errors, local recovery before escalation\n\n**Claude Code** — CLAUDE.md hierarchy, `@import`, `.claude/rules/` globs · commands and skills, project vs user scope, `context: fork`, `allowed-tools`, `argument-hint` · plan mode vs direct execution · iterative refinement patterns\n\n**Prompting and output** — structured output via `tool_use`, schema design, `tool_choice`, nullable fields against hallucination · few-shot for ambiguity, format consistency, false-positive reduction · batch processing appropriateness and failure handling by `custom_id`\n\n**Context and reliability** — trimming verbose tool output, structured fact extraction, position-aware ordering · escalation criteria and policy-gap identification · human review workflows, confidence calibration, stratified sampling, accuracy by segment · provenance: claim-source mappings, temporal data, conflict annotation, coverage gaps\n\n## Named technologies you should be able to recognize\n\n`stop_reason` (`\"tool_use\"`, `\"end_turn\"`) · `tool_use` with JSON schema · `tool_choice` (`\"auto\"`, `\"any\"`, forced) · `allowedTools` · Task tool · `AgentDefinition` · `PostToolUse` hooks · `fork_session` · `--resume` · `/memory` · `/compact` · Explore subagent · `-p` / `--print` · `--output-format json` · `--json-schema` · `.mcp.json` · `~/.claude.json` · `isError` · `errorCategory` · `isRetryable` · `.claude/rules/` · `.claude/commands/` · `.claude/skills/` with SKILL.md frontmatter · Message Batches API with `custom_id` · JSON Schema required/optional/enum/nullable · Pydantic validation · Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob\n\n> If a term is not on this page and not in a task statement, it is not worth exam time.",
   "ko": "**요지.** 가이드 §17 부록이 **\"시험에 안 나오는 것\"을 명시**한다. 가이드에서 가장 효율 높은 페이지 — 공부 시간을 돌려준다.\n\n**범위 밖(공부 금지):** 파인튜닝·모델훈련 / Claude 내부구조·훈련과정 / Constitutional AI·RLHF / API 인증·과금·계정 / OAuth·키 로테이션 / **MCP 서버 배포·호스팅(인프라·네트워킹·컨테이너)** / **스트리밍 API·SSE** / **prompt caching 구현 상세(\"존재한다\" 이상)** / **토큰 카운팅·토크나이징** / 레이트리밋·쿼터·가격계산 / 임베딩·벡터DB / computer use·vision / AWS·GCP·Azure 설정 / 벤치마킹·모델비교\n\n**특히 함정 3가지 — 사람들이 그래도 공부하는 것들:**\n1. **MCP 전송·서버 배포.** D2가 18%다 보니 stdio vs HTTP, 신뢰경계, 하드닝으로 파고들고 싶어진다. 그러나 공식 D2 목표는 **도구 설명 · 구조화 에러 · 도구 분배 · `.mcp.json` 스코프 · 내장 도구**다. 전송도 호스팅도 아니다.\n2. **prompt caching · token budgeting.** \"Context Management\"라는 이름 때문에 핵심처럼 들리지만, 실제 D5는 **정보를 보존하는 문제**다 — case facts, 에스컬레이션 기준, 에러 컨텍스트, 출처. 토큰을 세는 문제가 아니다.\n3. **스트리밍.** 아예 없다.\n\n**범위 안 = 30개 TS 그대로.** 부록의 in-scope 목록은 TS와 일대일로 대응한다.\n\n**알아봐야 할 이름들(부록 기술목록):** `stop_reason`(`\"tool_use\"`/`\"end_turn\"`) · `tool_use`+JSON schema · `tool_choice`(`\"auto\"`/`\"any\"`/forced) · `allowedTools` · Task 도구 · `AgentDefinition` · `PostToolUse` 훅 · `fork_session` · `--resume` · `/memory` · `/compact` · Explore subagent · `-p`/`--print` · `--output-format json` · `--json-schema` · `.mcp.json` · `~/.claude.json` · `isError` · `errorCategory` · `isRetryable` · `.claude/rules/` · `.claude/commands/` · `.claude/skills/` SKILL.md frontmatter · Message Batches API + `custom_id` · JSON Schema required/optional/enum/nullable · Pydantic · Read·Write·Edit·Bash·Grep·Glob\n\n> **이 페이지에도 없고 TS에도 없는 용어라면, 시험 시간을 쓸 가치가 없다.**"
